<div class="dablink">For the municipality on Crete see <a href="/wiki/Nikos_Kazantzakis_(municipality)" title="Nikos Kazantzakis (municipality)">Nikos Kazantzakis (municipality)</a>.</div>
<p><b>Nikos Kazantzakis</b> (<a href="/wiki/Greek_language" title="Greek language">Greek</a>: <span lang="el" xml:lang="el"><b>Νίκος Καζαντζάκης</b></span>) (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1883-02-18"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="02-18"><a href="/wiki/February_18" title="February 18">February 18</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1883" title="1883">1883</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/Heraklion" title="Heraklion">Heraklion</a>, <a href="/wiki/Crete" title="Crete">Crete</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ottoman_Empire" title="Ottoman Empire">Ottoman Empire</a> - <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1957-10-26"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="10-26"><a href="/wiki/October_26" title="October 26">October 26</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1957" title="1957">1957</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/Freiburg" title="Freiburg" class="mw-redirect">Freiburg</a>, <a href="/wiki/Germany" title="Germany">Germany</a>) was arguably the most important and most translated <a href="/wiki/Greece" title="Greece">Greek</a> <a href="/wiki/Writer" title="Writer">writer</a> and <a href="/wiki/Philosopher" title="Philosopher" class="mw-redirect">philosopher</a> of the 20th century. Yet he did not become well known globally until the 1964 release of the <a href="/wiki/Michael_Cacoyannis" title="Michael Cacoyannis">Michael Cacoyannis</a> film <i><a href="/wiki/Zorba_the_Greek_(film)" title="Zorba the Greek (film)">Zorba the Greek</a></i>, based on Kazantzakis' <a href="/wiki/Zorba_the_Greek" title="Zorba the Greek">novel</a> whose English translation has the same title.</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
